history.content:
Here's your course website: https://sp19.datastructur.es

It's empty, so here's the website from last year, from when Professor Hug last taught the course: https://sp18.datastructur.es

This course is a little more prone to change than CS 61A, but a lot of the advice I gave in the other post (@8362) still applies - the best way to learn the material is to go through the lectures, discussions, and assignments. In addition, there's a recommended textbook (though not required) called Head First Java that is used as a supplement during the first part of the course covering Java, which you may want to pick up and read through on your own first to make adjusting to the class next semester a little easier.

children.subject: I would say just get comfortable with Java as your first priority. That's definitely going to free you up to pay more attention to the actual course content (data structures at first will be your main thing). If you feel like you're ahead and have free time and have Java down pretty well, then I'd just look at last years course site and start going through the lectures ahead (which after data structures will MAINLY be trees and sorting and various algorithms).
Thanks. Is there anyone else who has taken the course who can provide input?
I prepared by practicing some basic Java programming on Hackerrank and watching previous webcasts.

In addition to the lectures/guides on the course website, I wrote a textbook for the course if you'd like to check it out:

http://www.kartikkapur.com/documents/DataStructuresAndAlgorithms.pdf 

Getting an introduction to Java would definitely help. 

That being said try to avoid stressing too much over break :)
